  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What should I do to get selected in GSOC 2018?",
  "response": "Google Summer of Code (GSoC) is a highly competitive program that offers students the opportunity to work on open-source projects under the guidance of mentors from various organizations. Although the specific details for GSoC 2018 are now outdated, the general strategies for getting selected remain relevant for future iterations of the program. Here are steps you can take to increase your chances of being accepted into GSoC:\n\n### 1. **Understand GSoC**\n\n- **Program Structure**: GSoC runs annually during the summer, where students work on projects proposed by participating organizations.\n- **Eligibility**: Typically, students should be at least 18 years old and enrolled in an accredited institution or be a recent graduate.\n\n### 2. **Choose the Right Organization**\n\n- **Research Organizations**: Review the list of participating organizations from previous years to identify those aligned with your interests and skills.\n- **Understand Their Projects**: Visit the organization's website and read through their past and proposed projects to find areas where you can contribute effectively.\n\n### 3. **Engage with the Community Early**\n\n- **Join Communication Channels**: Most organizations have mailing lists, forums, IRC channels, or Slack groups. Start engaging with them early.\n- **Contribute to Discussions**: Participate in discussions, ask questions, and show genuine interest in the projects.\n- **Submit Small Contributions**: Begin by contributing to the codebase or documentation. This demonstrates your commitment and ability to work within the community.\n\n### 4. **Select a Project Carefully**\n\n- **Choose a Project That Matches Your Skills**: Select projects that align with your expertise while also offering room for growth.\n- **Reach Out to Potential Mentors**: Contact mentors to discuss your interest and seek feedback on your potential contributions.\n\n### 5. **Develop a Strong Proposal**\n\n- **Follow Guidelines**: Adhere strictly to the proposal guidelines provided by GSoC.\n- **Clearly Define Your Project**: Outline the problem you're addressing, your proposed solution, and the steps you will take to implement it.\n- **Set Realistic Milestones**: Break down your project into manageable tasks with achievable timelines.\n- **Highlight Your Qualifications**: Showcase your relevant skills, past projects, and contributions to demonstrate your capability to handle the project.\n- **Proofread**: Ensure your proposal is free from grammatical errors and is well-structured.\n\n### 6. **Showcase Your Skills**\n\n- **Build a Portfolio**: Maintain a GitHub (or similar) profile with your projects, contributions, and any relevant work.\n- **Include Previous Contributions**: Highlight any previous open-source contributions, especially to the organization you're applying to.\n- **Demonstrate Problem-Solving Abilities**: Share examples where you've successfully tackled challenges in your projects.\n\n### 7. **Seek Feedback**\n\n- **Get Input on Your Proposal**: Share your proposal draft with mentors or peers to receive constructive feedback.\n- **Iterate Accordingly**: Make necessary revisions based on the feedback to improve the quality of your proposal.\n\n### 8. **Stay Informed About Timelines**\n\n- **Application Period**: Be aware of the application periods and deadlines. Missing deadlines can disqualify your application.\n- **Prepare in Advance**: Start preparing your application well before the deadline to ensure you have ample time to refine it.\n\n### 9. **Prepare for the Coding Phase**\n\n- **Develop Your Project Plan**: Have a clear understanding of how you will execute the project once selected.\n- **Stay Organized**: Use tools like GitHub Issues, Trello, or other project management tools to track your progress.\n\n### 10. **Stay Persistent**\n\n- **Learn from Rejections**: If you're not selected, seek feedback, improve your skills, and consider applying again in the future.\n- **Continuous Engagement**: Even if you're not selected, continue contributing to open-source projects to build your profile.\n\n### Additional Resources\n\n- **[GSoC Official Website](https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/)**: For the latest information on application cycles, guidelines, and participating organizations.\n- **[Previous Year's Proposals](https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/archive/)**: Reviewing successful proposals can provide insights into what works well.\n- **[GSoC Forums and Communities](https://www.reddit.com/r/soc/)**: Engage with past participants to learn from their experiences.\n\nBy following these steps and demonstrating genuine passion and commitment to open-source development, you can significantly enhance your chances of being selected for GSoC. Good luck!",
